Most popular are supermarkets and laundromats. Coincidentally, these businesses are very popular among local residents, as quality of food in the supermarkets are superb, the prices are much cheaper, and finally yet importantly, it is very convenient. Just nearby where I am, there are four Asian supermarkets within two minutes of walking distance from each other. This just adds to the convenience of accessing grocery. I’m not saying Bensonhurst is purely populated by Asian inhabitants, though. It is quite diverse all around, with immigrants and their first-generation and second-generation American children here. Most of the large and popular businesses in the local area are Asian owned. In addition to these Asian owned businesses, there is also a recently renovated park nearby, which has around ten basketball courts, a large field for soccer or baseball, four handball courts, swings, a playground for kids, and even a water fountain for kids to enjoy water in the summer. Since we are in New York City, of course the parks are very diverse. You will see all sorts of diversity here, able to play and get along well. In this neighborhood, there aren’t many large corporate buildings. The only buildings you’d find are ones for co-op living, or condominium apartments. The majority of living spaces here are two-family houses though. Most of the people are quite nice, however, very noisy. Every day, you’d hear cars blasting their music as they drive by your house, or constantly flooring the gas on their cars which will wake you up in the morning. If you are planning on visiting during night time, you should be on your guard. This neighborhood is fairly safe, but people are unpredictable. You may run into people who want to start trouble for no reason, bullies and thieves. I myself have been bullied in this neighborhood in the past via physical assault, but this was many years ago. Another recent incident involved package stealing. Although a common thing, there are package thieves in this neighborhood. Last but not least, although New York City has a fine for people not cleaning up after their dogs, people don’t follow the rules here. Every morning, you will see at least one dog waste on your way to the train station, or on your way to the supermarket. My biggest pet peeve is dog waste on the floor everywhere I go in this neighborhood. Be careful and keep your shoes clean!
The first thing you have to understand about Portland, Oregon is the definition of "weird". The unofficial town slogan, on the back of a building that serves as a pizza joint, bar, music venue, strip club, and skirts the law on at least half of these endeavors, is "Keep Portland Weird". To some, this is a small cry to remember the Portland of the 90's and early 2000's, a Portland that was less known and less expensive, generating creative and unique subcultures. To others, it is a beckoning call - come to Portland, where people will still call you weird, but as a compliment this time. Despite the influx of affluent Californians and the constant construction of condominiums to house these Californians, Portland is still weird. Weird does not mean always accepting, but it does mean accepting of things that are normally not accepted. Weird does not mean we do not have modern conveniences and modern fights. Like the rest of the country, we buy most of our things from China. There are a million ways of being weird, of being not normal, but Portland has plenty of normal. Portland has yoga and hipsters and business professionals. Perhaps weird means we just take all of this less seriously. In my neighborhood, as in many Portland neighborhoods, we have colorful houses, home gardens with flowers and herbs and vegetables lining the streets, and free boxes in the summertime. Free boxes are traditionally cardboard boxes containing items someone is getting rid of, but they can be plastic bags or boxes. They contain something magical, a treasure just perfect for the person wandering by, a surprising amount of the time. Free boxes tend to have clothes and books, but they can have anything. The magical potential of walking through a Southeast Portland neighborhood is what Portland is all about. That is, what Portland is all about to me, but I am just one variety of weird among thousands. Some people I live among would never dream of picking their clothes out of a box on the sidewalk. Those people go to goat yoga (yes, yoga with real live goats) or Timbers matches (the city's soccer team). Portland is full of people who love all sorts of things. Portland is full of people who pursue our dreams, or dream about pursuing our dreams while spending too much time at the bar. Yes, Portland has a drug problem. Drug problems tend to be (at their root) mental health problems, and the constant rain through much of the year, plus the dreary clouds, appear to be a contributor. Portland has a homelessness problem too, which no one seems to know what to do with. The homeless population is drawn by the social services Portland offers, better than in most parts of the country, but our services are insufficient, as in all parts of the country. The non-homeless population wavers between care and hatred. In this, we are not weird at all.
The mountains are always there. In the north, bearing witness to the sun’s journey every dawn and every dusk. No matter how much I forget about them or how caught up with work and life I am to notice, they are there, unwavering, unopposed, and unphased by life’s tribulations. Then on days when I am the most stressed and wound, they demand to be seen, and when I turn to them they let me rest my anxious soul, lending me some strength to go on, one day at a time. I first moved here when I started my undergrad, and the mountains to the north of campus where what first captivated me. Sure, the university has its own share of breathtaking sights in buildings and ponds and trees, which have their own share of my heart, but it’s the mountains that really holds its throne. The rest of the town is beautiful in its own right. There are countless cafés that were home to many hours of caffeine fueled cramming. One can walk or take the bus just a little further to the downtown area and be enveloped in an aura of antiquity by the faded colored bricks that line restaurants and office buildings. It is here that this seemingly suburban town shows as much bustle and vigor as it’s neighboring urban city. This doesn’t last for many blocks though, as one can escape, once again, to the serene small town by passing the library. This dichotomy of atmospheres in such proximity truly give this city a wonderous vibe as if it was beckoning to be explored. With this, it is easy to create many a cherished memory, each in association with a certain part of town. Whether it is walking past the rusted swings in the park with friends after an all-nighter or running through the busy downtown to catch the movie in the fancy theater for which the university provided tickets. Alas, it is also home to many harsh memories, as all places are bound to be in life. The ponds, in particular, can be a rather fitting place for reflection as well as crying sessions at two in the morning in the middle of an existential crisis. The latter of which, I have more experience in. While watching the turtles and ducks and insects live out their lives, each with some contribution or role, I couldn’t help but wonder about my own sense of purpose as I struggled to navigate this mystery called life. So, I walked past the pond, and past the park and little houses that scream of suburbia, until I reached a main street. It was then that sun shined its brilliant rays atop the palm trees, painting the sky along the way, and as I looked up at the sunrise, I realized I was walking north. Sure enough, they were there, as they had always been. The sturdy overbearing mountains grazed the hazy blue and yellow sky more than any building in the horizon, and as if speaking without words, stirred in me my sense of perseverance.
You might pass it up on first glance - after all, it is a residential area behind a shopping strip, not a place one would assume there are places to live. At least, not places most people would want to live. But if you go behind the old, abandoned Whole Foods and walk back behind the hotels which are only occupied annually aside from a few stints in the summertime for family reunions, you'll find an entire bustling community. Within these communities, on these streets, are a handful of apartment complex - situated next to each other carefully like Russian nesting dolls that have been scrupulously, carefully taken apart and set beside each other in a line down the road, piecemeal. The first apartments you come upon are ones which have been on the news for some fairly unsavory dealings, so we won't focus on those too much - appearances, after all, can be deceiving. But the apartments beside that complex, and the two complexes beside that one, are a whole other world that almost no one living in this area knows about. Across from those complexes is a community college's satellite campus - a quiet, sleepy set of buildings standing sentinel beside the road, where students putter in with coffee in hand, yawning at 7 in the morning to begin their sleepy days. The iron gates creak open to admit them one by one, while commuters shake their fists out the window and groan at them for holding up traffic on days attendance is higher. The road t-bones into another residential road, with a park on one side and a rehabilitation center for people who have broken bones in unfortunate circumstances. The treatment center boasts cheerful porch furniture, and a lazily undulating ceiling fan which churns the warm, thick summertime air back and forth. Children run back and forth in the grass at the park across the street, cartwheeling and pinwheeling across the prickly green stalks while bees lazily turn in the flower patches by the road. Old retired folks walk their dogs on the walking path, scowling at the teenagers on their skateboards and nodding demurely at the teenage girls clustered by the playground equipment, gossiping about boys and the latest YouTube sensations. There is a sushi place in a strip mall beside the park that has inexpensive food but never seems too busy - a swimming supply store right beside that, and a nail salon nestled in between. You could fill your pool for the season while getting a manicure and eating hibachi chicken, all at once - the beauty of a strip mall. There is a frozen yogurt place there too, one of the DIY kind, and you often see the teens in the park clutching cold, sweating cups of frozen yogurt covered in toppings while they do stunts on their skateboards and vape because they believe it to be the coolest. The neighborhood in question is a slice of Americana - a piece of history in the sleepy south where hardly anything changes, not even time.
My neighborhood is interesting. Most of the houses are single family, but there are a few homes that have been split into two, while still being attached, if that makes much sense. My home has a small yard in front of it and a small driveway to the left of the house. It, like most of the others, reminds you of a time not so long ago where living in the suburbs was the American dream. This dream at once seemed to embrace the people of this country, but now its pulling away. But my neighborhood and many more still remain, still call out to us and those who visit that the dream is still alive, and we are still holding onto it as best we can. The people don't feel as optomistic as they used to, the upkeep of the little yards are not what they used to be, but there is still a car or two in every driveway, still the youth play as if the world around them was the whole of their existence. The public school that has been here for almost 90 years still stands, still seems conjure a future in today's youth, while stirring up nostalgia in the older residents. The churches are few and far between, mostly empty, but the basketball courts are still full. All of the homes look different, but feel the same. There is a large supermarket called super "A" that has been owned by a large Yemni family, who are quite possible the only Arab family in the neighborhood. The vast majority of the residents are African American. The streets are wide and the kids usually play footbal, only stopping to allow the cars to pass. Most of the people in my neighborhood have been here for generations and most can tell stories of a past where everyone knew everyone. There was a karate school, but when hollywood stopped making karate kid movies, the kids stopped wanting to be the karate kid, so its now a pharmacy, because drugs make everything better, or so I've heard. There is also a small movie theatre that plays old movies at a discounted price, spared from the crowds by the youth's disdane for its lack of just release titles, but favored by the elders, who think it is a small price to pay for a night out, without the kids of course. There is a single expressway that passes through my town. Though the exit and entrance are in the town next to ours. There was once a petition to get and exit for our town. The youth supported it, while the elders refused. It seems that having the expressway in our town would ruin it, so said the elders who eventually persuaded the city council to deny the request. They are building a new highschool, and we are trying to decide on a mascott for our town. I think a cyborg with a country accent and a log cabin would be then best representation of my town.
Since I live in a large city, my neighborhood is extremely diverse. Residential areas are dispersed, seemingly randomly, between commercial areas, where a variety of businesses are run. Some of these businesses are made up of offices, while others are various stores, restaurants, and places of entertainment. There is no shortage of new restaurants to eat at, or stores to shop in. While some stores are large, well-known, brands that are owned by large corporations, small boutiques are also increasingly popular. They are not only located in various malls, but they also line the streets, which are often in walking distance of neighborhoods that would otherwise be quiet and serene, if not surrounded by so many points of interest. There are also a couple of nearby parks, and I have noticed that people frequent these parks with their young children. Speaking of the people, thereâ€™s actually quite a bit of diversity within my neighborhood. In one small location, we have a prominent LGBTQ+ community, an Orthodox Jewish community, and a collection of refugees and immigrants from the former Soviet Union. Spanning a little further outside of my neighborhood, there are many more individuals of various races and origins, although they are sometimes broken up into their own little communities within the city. We have locations known as Korea town, China town, Little Armenia, and many more, which are only a few miles away. However, only a few miles can prove to be a very lengthy drive. Driving a distance of only 10 miles can sometimes span two hours, due to traffic, especially during rush hour. Hardly anyone in my city walks anywhere, though. While certain locations of interest are inevitably close-by, the city is huge, and people do not generally prefer to commute on foot. As a result, we also have some of the worst traffic in the world, and it can be difficult to find parking spots just about anywhere. Ironically enough, there has been a great deal of construction in recent years, as large apartment buildings are being added to the city. It is seems to be a popular destination, but many residents are disappointed by the prospect of even more people moving in, and even more vehicles on the roads. There are many different types of houses in my city, however. Not everyone lives, or wishes to live, in a large apartment building. Residential areas are made up of houses, of various sizes, and smaller apartment buildings and condominiums. Some properties contain single-family homes, while others contain duplexes. This is true even within my immediately neighborhood, so there is also no lack of diversity in regards to housing options. Similarly, the neighborhood is made up of people of varying ages, and to be perfectly honest, I am not familiar with the majority of my neighbors. It is not really a tight-knit community these days, although I have many memories from my childhood of playing outside with my next-door neighbor, and a few other friends from the neighborhood, who were all close to my age.
“Where is everything?” she asked as we drove past the corn fields which filled the horizon. “This is it!” I said, knowing she’d be in shock of the sparseness of the open landscape. She was from a town in which the grocery store was a 5 minute walk from her house--she’d never seen this much open space in her life. Taken back by the ubiquity of corn fields, I shared with her what it was like to grow up in rural Ohio, and in that moment, she finally knew who I was and where I came from. Driving down a two-lane country road, you will reach a quarry which is filled with water. Just past it is the small development I live in. The houses are mostly composed of brick and stucco. All the houses have at least a half an acre of land to themselves which everyone takes pride in maintaining. During springtime, annually planted flowers are abundant along with the midwestern trees that change with every season. The driveways are all filled with the highest end Mercedes Benz luxury cars that glisten in the midday sun after a good, old-fashioned car wash. Continuing along the road toward my grey stucco home, my Korean neighbor is always outside with a friendly face. He tends to spend the entire day mowing his lawn and can be heard singing over his mower’s hum. Everyone in the neighborhood gets a laugh out of him, but he is always genuine and an amazing person with a unique history. He has grown older and has lost some of his wit as he aged. In his past he was a doctor and usually blends in with the grass and his John Deer Zero Turn mower. Finally, you will reach my home. In the side yard, geese are abundant and are chased by our Terrier. Out back, there is a small stream that feeds into the quarry. Here, you can hear bullfrogs, the stream, and the occasional “moo” from the nearby farms. Across the handmade wooden bridge is an untouched oasis filled with naturally growing trees, herbs, and wildflowers. Here was where I spent most of my childhood. From building tree forts to ‘hunting’ animals (which mostly consisted of chasing them), there was always something to do and usually a neighborhood child available for friendship. The winters in my small town can be painfully brutal, yet there is nothing more beautiful. The yard transforms from a sea of green into an empty wilderness. The trees that once housed vibrant pink, purple, and orange flowers turn into barren skeletons of bark. When blessed with the occasional snowfall, a winter wonderland appears overnight. The backyard is lined with snow angels made by my little sister, and snowmen. My sister and I fought frequently as kids, and during the winter, snowballs were our weapon of choice. We’d build massive igloo-like forts to house our weapons, usually with branches, like an arsenal. In our own little wonderland was where we played pretend during a time where nothing else mattered. We were just young kids without a care in the world.

There are many new restaurants to eat at and stores to buy things in. Some parks are near my home. People often visit these parks with their young children. My neighborhood is very diverse. Many different kinds of people live here. There is a group of people who support LGBTQ+ rights. Another group is Orthodox Jewish. We also have people who came from the Soviet Union. Some people from Korea, China, and Armenia live in other areas of the city. These areas are not far from my neighborhood.

But the city is very big. It takes a long time to drive even a short distance. This is because of traffic. Many people in the city do not walk anywhere. They drive instead. The city has a lot of traffic problems. It is hard to find a place to park.

The city is growing. New buildings are being built. Some people are happy about this. But others are not. They do not want more people and cars in the city. There are many different kinds of homes in the city. Some people live in apartments. Others live in houses or small buildings. Some homes have only one family. Others have two families.

I do not know most of my neighbors. We are not close like we used to be when I was a child. But I have good memories of playing with my friends in the neighborhood.

My neighborhood is interesting. Most houses here are for one family. But some houses are divided into two parts. My house has a small yard in front and a small driveway. It looks like the houses in this area many years ago. Many people in this country thought living in the suburbs was the American dream. This dream made people happy, but now people are not as happy. My neighborhood still looks like the American dream. There is a school here for almost ninety years. The school still makes students think about the future. It also makes older people remember the past. There are few churches in my neighborhood. They are mostly empty. But there are two basketball courts. Many people play basketball there.

There is a big store called Super A. It belongs to an Arab family who is one of the few Arab families here. Most people in my neighborhood are African American. The streets are wide. Children play football there. They stop playing when a car comes. Many people in my neighborhood have lived here for a long time. They know everyone. There was a school for karate. But people don't want to be a karate hero like in the movies anymore. So, now it is a pharmacy. People think medicine makes everything better. There is a small movie theater that shows old movies at a low price. Young people don't like it because it does not show new movies. Older people like it because it is cheap and fun.

We have one highway that goes through our town. The entrance and exit are in the town next to ours. People wanted to put an entrance and exit in our town, but some people said it would ruin our town. They were right, so the city said no. We are building a new high school. We are trying to choose a symbol for our town. I think a robot who likes the country and lives in a small house would be a good symbol for our town.

You might not think this is a place to live. It's behind a shopping area. But if you walk behind the old store and the hotels, you will find a community. It is a neighborhood with apartments. These apartments are next to each other like boxes. Some people have known problems at one of the apartments. We will not talk about that one. The other apartments are a different story. They are a secret many people do not know about.

Across from the apartments is a school. Students come here to learn. They drink coffee and wake up slowly. The gates open, and they enter one by one. People in cars are not happy when they see them because it slows down the traffic. The road divides into another street. There is a park on one side and a place to help people who hurt themselves. The house has a nice porch and a big fan. Children play in the park. They run and play on the grass. People walk their dogs and look at the teenagers skateboarding. The teenagers talk to each other by the playground equipment.

There is a restaurant that serves sushi. It is not very busy. There is also a store that sells swimming supplies and a place to get a manicure. You can fill your pool and get a manicure at the same time. There is also a shop that sells frozen yogurt. Teens eat frozen yogurt and drink it while they skateboard and vape. This neighborhood is special. It shows what America is like in a quiet place where time does not change quickly.

We drove past many fields of corn. My friend asked, "Where is everything?" I said, "This is it." The open landscape was very different from where she lived. In her town, a store was just a short walk from her house. But here, there is much open space.

I told her about growing up in rural Ohio. She was surprised. For the first time, she understood where I came from. We drove down a country road. We passed a big water-filled hole called a quarry. Near it is the small place where I live. The houses are made of brick and stucco. Each house has a big yard. People are proud of their yards.

In the spring, many flowers grow. So do trees that change color with the seasons. People wash their cars and they shine in the sun. We continued driving. My neighbor is always outside. He smiles and is friendly. He mows his lawn all day. He sings while he works. Everyone laughs at him, but he is a good person. He worked as a doctor a long time ago.

We came to my house. There are many geese in the yard. Our dog chases them. A small stream runs into the quarry. You can hear frogs, the stream, and cows from nearby farms. Across a small bridge is a special place. It is full of trees, herbs, and flowers that grow naturally. This is where I spent my childhood.

I built forts in the trees. I also "hunted" animals. Really, I just chased them. I had friends from my neighborhood to play with. Our town can be very cold in the winter. But it is also very beautiful. The trees are empty and look like skeletons. Sometimes it snows and the yard looks like a winter wonderland. My sister made snow angels and snowmen. We fought a lot when we were kids. But in the winter, we built forts and fought with snowballs. We played pretend and had fun.

Portland, Oregon is a special city. The city's unofficial saying is "Keep Portland Weird". To some people, this means remembering the old Portland from the 90's and early 2000's. This Portland was not well-known and not expensive. It had new and different subcultures. To others, it is a call to come to Portland. Here, people think it is a compliment to be called "weird". 

Many rich people from California have moved to Portland. The city is building many new homes for them. But Portland is still a little strange. It does not always mean being strange is good. Strange people accept things others do not. We have modern things like everyone else. We buy many things from China. 

There are many ways to be strange. Portland has normal things too. We have yoga, hipsters, and business people. Maybe strange people just do not take things seriously. In my neighborhood, the houses are colorful. There are flowers and herbs in the gardens. People put free things outside in the summer. These things are often clothes and books. Sometimes you can find other things. 

Walking through a neighborhood in Portland is special. This is what Portland is all about. But people are different. Some people will never take free things from the sidewalk. They go to a place for goat yoga or a soccer game. Portland has many people who like different things. Many people chase their dreams. Some people like to spend time at the bar. Portland has a problem with drugs. This is often a problem with mental health. The rain and clouds here may make it worse. Portland also has a problem with homeless people. No one knows how to solve this problem. More people are coming to Portland for help. But we do not have enough help. Some people are kind to the homeless. Others do not like them. This is not strange. It is just life.

The mountains are always there. They watch the sun rise and set in the north. They do not change. They do not forget. They do not worry. I forget about them sometimes. I get busy with work and life. But they are always there. 

When I am stressed, I see them. They help me feel better. They give me the strength to go on. I first came here when I was a student. The mountains near the university were beautiful. The university has many nice buildings, ponds, and trees. But the mountains are special. They have my heart. The town is nice too. There are many cafes where I studied for hours. I can walk or take a bus to the city center. It is an old town. The buildings are old and small. But it is still active. I can walk to the library and be in a quiet place. This town has different feelings in different parts. It is a mix of calm and busy. I like this. I have many good memories here. I remember walking with friends in the park. We were tired from studying all night. I also remember going to the movies in the city center. I have bad memories too. We all have bad memories in life. The ponds are a good place to think. I sat by the ponds many times and thought about my life. I wondered what my purpose was. I saw turtles, ducks, and insects living their lives. They all have a job. They all live their lives. I thought about my life and my job. I walked to the main street. The sun was shining. The sky was blue and yellow. I looked up and saw the mountains. They were still there. They were strong and big. They made me feel strong and brave. They told me to keep going.

If you plan to visit Bensonhurt, Brooklyn, you will not have trouble finding it. Public transportation is easy to use. Bensonhurt is a busy neighborhood in New York City. You will feel like you are in a big city. Many Asian stores are here. Over 20 years, Bensonhurt has gotten more Asian people. You will see an Asian store on almost every block. The stores are popular. Many are supermarkets and laundromats. These businesses are popular because the food is good, the prices are low, and they are convenient. I live here. There are four Asian supermarkets near my home. They are all within a two-minute walk from each other. This is very helpful. Bensonhurt is not just Asian. There are people from different countries and their American-born children. Many businesses are Asian-owned. There is also a park near here. It has basketball courts, a soccer/baseball field, handball courts, swings, and a water fountain. People from different countries play together here. Bensonhurt has many two-family houses. There are a few big buildings for apartments. People are generally nice, but noisy. Cars with loud music often pass by. You may hear a car screeching its tires in the morning. If you visit at night, be careful. This area is safe, but some people can be angry or try to fight. I was bullied in the past, but that was many years ago. Sometimes, people steal packages. Dog owners do not clean up after their dogs. You will see dog waste on the sidewalk every morning. I do not like this. Be careful and keep your shoes clean.

Where I live, there are not many sidewalks. The ground slopes downward, and my house is at the top. People call this hill the "work out hill." Many people run up the hill during their daily exercise. There are no sidewalks on my street, so everyone walks on the road. The road is not good in some places and can be a little bit dangerous to drive on.

The telephone and electric wires around my neighborhood look old and broken. This is because it often rains and storms here. Branches from trees hit the wires and cause damage. The repairs make the wires look bad. There are many tall evergreen trees around. But people here do not like the trees. They cut them down because the trees block the view of the ocean. Many houses are built high on the hill with big windows to see the ocean.

The view is beautiful at sunset. The water shines and the sky is orange. But it is often cloudy, so the sun is hidden by fog. Most days are overcast and damp. Moss grows on everything outside. It even grows on cars. I once left my car outside for a month and there was a lot of moss on it. It took me three hours to clean it off.

There are not many children in my neighborhood. There is a school near here. Most people in my neighborhood are older and retired. They have dogs instead of children. Dogs are common in our neighborhood. They run around in people's yards and in the street. If you leave a door or window open, they might get into your house. I once found a dog in my living room and had to chase it out. Rabbits run around the area. They are big and can dig up gardens. My cats like them, but they can be a problem. We also see small birds, hummingbirds, and hawks. The neighborhood crows chase the hawks away.

There are no stores near my house. But if you walk downhill to the waterfront, there are some restaurants that serve fresh seafood. The beach is not very big, but you can throw rocks into the water. The bay is not very wide. You can see the other side even on cloudy days.

I live in a small town in Tennessee. My house is on a street between two main roads. This makes the street busier than I like. But it's still a quiet neighborhood. Not many people move in and out, so I know most of my neighbors. They usually do yard work and other daily tasks. In the winter, we sled on a hill near my house.

My house is on a corner, so we see all the people and cars going by. When we see a strange car, we notice it. Some neighbors walk for exercise or to walk their dogs. Kids ride their bikes and play outside. We work from home, so we are there a lot. I have a wife and two daughters, aged 11 and 14. So, the other neighbors are used to us coming and going.

We go outside and play, even when it rains. We also have a deck where we grill sometimes. The smell of barbecue is nice. You can hear lawn mowers almost every day from March to October. This is because we have many trees and leaves in the fall. We have to rake and burn them each year. I like the smell of burning leaves.

We don't have much winter, so it feels like a long fall. Our garage is in the back of the house. I like to work on my truck there. When the garage doors are open, I feel connected to the neighborhood. On holidays, it's quiet. But some neighbors visit from out of town on holidays like Thanksgiving and Christmas. I like living here. If the street weren't a main road, it would be perfect.

My neighborhood is in a dry desert. It is very brown. People who have not lived here may not know what it is like. They do not see green grass. When they see green grass, they know the owner of the house is spending a lot of money to take care of it.

When I first lived here, houses were far apart. Now, there are more houses. The neighborhood is getting like a big city. But it is like this in many places. Most people are friendly. My neighborhood is nice. There are many old people who are friendly.

The stores in my neighborhood are big chains like Food 4 Less and Smart & Final. If you want to buy natural food, you must go elsewhere. The main jobs in my city are in construction. This is because the city is not fully built. There is much empty space to build.

I work in construction. My job is to install drywall and T-bars. I am afraid of the city growing too much. I like it the way it is now. I came from a big city and I do not want to go back.

I like my neighborhood because of the animals. Many people come to the desert for its beauty. The desert is hard to live in, but it is home to many animals. We must learn about the animals to live safely and peacefully with them.

My family and I like the animals. My children are very interested in lizards and desert bugs. They are outside now trying to catch them.

There are things to see in my neighborhood. Victorville is a good place for families to learn about the desert. The San Bernardino County Fair is an event you should not miss. It has many activities and fun things to do. You can also go to Wrightwood to see the snow and learn to ski.

If you are interested in the desert and its history, visit the Victor Valley Museum. It has rocks, dinosaur bones, and things from Native American people. These things tell us about the history of Victorville.

I live in a college campus. My home is a dormitory. My community is the people who live in my dorm. I also think of the campus around my dorm as my neighborhood. My neighborhood is special. It is not like a usual neighborhood. I am happy to tell you about my neighborhood.

My neighborhood has different kinds of houses. Some houses are apartments. These have 2 to 4 people in each room. There are 4 to 6 rooms on each floor. One building can house 20 people. Another kind of house is for people who rent. These houses have 2 to 4 bedrooms. They are not very common. Most of the houses in my neighborhood are dorm rooms. These rooms have 2 people in each room. Many students live in these rooms.

My neighborhood is very diverse. People from all over the world live here. They are of different ages. The people who work here live in the houses. New students live in the dorm rooms. Older students live in the apartments. My neighborhood has many stores. These stores sell food, clothes and other things you need. My school has its own stores. You can find everything you need in my neighborhood. We also have a park. It is a safe and clean place for everyone to play.

I have lived in this neighborhood for about 10 years. It was hard for me when I first moved here. I missed my friends and family in Riverdale. My parents wanted a better home and school for me and my sister. We moved to Stockbridge. 

I made some new friends, but I also had some enemies at school. I did not know my neighbors well, except for Mr. Glen and his family. They are good people. I like them. They feel like family to me.

I remember Mr. Glen's wedding. It was fun. I'm glad I went. I want to have a wedding like that someday. I want to give my future wife a good life.

Mr. Glen's wife, Ms. Veda, threw her shoe, and I caught it. I also saw her flowers, but I didn't catch them. We danced and had fun. I liked spending time with Marsharii, Mr. Glen's daughter.

The neighborhood is like a maze. I use a GPS to find my way around. I like to explore. I go to the park and enjoy nature. It helps me feel calm. I also like to practice my balance with sticks and my wooden sword.

There is a basketball and tennis court. I used to play tennis with my dad and my best friend. We had a good time. We worked hard, but we had fun.

I have had a lot of good times in this neighborhood. I have many stories. I think the best is yet to come.

I live near the college I attend. I like living here. It is close to the school. There are many apartment buildings. Some restaurants and bars are near my home. They are not very expensive. I go to one of the bars sometimes. It is a little more expensive, but the service and drinks are good.

Most people in my neighborhood are students or have low incomes. They can afford to live here because rent is not high. There is an elementary school near my apartment. I see many children playing outside.

I don't know my neighbors very well. They smoke a lot of marijuana. The management put a special air freshener in front of their door. My boyfriend and I think it is funny.

The buildings around me are old. Some of them have been fixed up inside. Down the street, there are new apartments. I don't like them. They are not well built, but the rent is high. I think it is not fair.

There is a cheap restaurant near my home. They serve food on paper plates and most of the food is heated in a microwave. Across from the restaurant is a gas station. I heard it is a hard place to work.

The city fixed the road near my home last summer. Now it is nicer. There is a big sidewalk, grass, and trees. My apartment building has many trees. Some of them were cut down, but there are still many trees around.

Behind my apartment is a line of trees and another apartment building. I live on 42nd Street. Next to it is 43rd Street. It is not as nice. The sidewalks are broken and the buildings look old. There are many trees on this street, but they hide how bad the buildings look. There is a lot of crime on this street, mainly in one apartment complex. But it is not the only place with problems.

I like where I live. I can afford it, and there are many things I need near my home. I like that the university is close and there are bus stops to get to the store and downtown easily.

My neighborhood is made of special houses called duplexes. They are placed so they look like separate houses. Each one is painted yellow with a white porch and a green roof. Most people in the neighborhood are friends with each other. We stand at the end of a driveway some evenings and talk. Children play outside with toys, chalk, or kites. It is nice to live here in a world with many machines.

It is like going back in time to a simpler place. We have fields and trees with blue skies and white, fluffy clouds. But sometimes we get warnings of big storms called tornadoes. Last night, we heard a siren and went to a safe place. I was in the bathtub with my little dog and a few pillows. My big dog stayed in the living room, barking nervously. The neighborhood was quiet except for the sound of big hail hitting the ground.

After the storm, the road was very hot. The temperature changed and the hail melted. The sun came out and it started to rain. A beautiful rainbow appeared. I quickly took pictures with my camera. The streets were quiet for a long time after the storm. People slowly came home from being out. Then it was like normal again. Moms and kids were outside and dinner was cooking.

I like this neighborhood a lot. I moved here from New Hampshire. I like hearing the southern accent. All the apartments look the same on the outside, but they are not the same inside. Some are very small. I enjoy walking in a big field behind my house. There is a small pond there. I have seen deer and heard a big frog singing in the morning. It is a great place to live, near the city of Charlotte. Each morning, I hear roosters crowing from the farms around here. It feels like I am in a small village. We also have a donkey that brays in the evening. I am lucky to live here.

I moved to this neighborhood when I started eighth grade. It was hard to make friends at first, but I became close to two people who lived nearby. They do not live here anymore, but I still remember them.

Some people who lived here when I moved here are still living here. My neighborhood is like many American neighborhoods. There are many two-story houses here. People usually play outside when the weather is warm.

The neighborhood is quiet most days. I have never had a problem with anyone in the neighborhood. People respect each other's space here.

There is a park near my house. I have good memories there. I played sports with my friends there. I also got hurt playing football, but the good times are more important.

Now, I visit the park to spend time with my younger cousin's children. They like to play on the swings and slide. Just thinking about the park makes me feel happy and sad at the same time.

My neighborhood is different from many other neighborhoods. You can find many kinds of food near here. There are Chinese, Indian, Mexican, and Italian restaurants. Many people order food from apps like GrubHub and DoorDash.

There are many stores here with everything you need. There are places to clean your clothes, a pharmacy, and a grocery store. There is an Indian store too, where you can buy Indian food or make your own.

I like my neighborhood. I see bad things on social media and the news about neighbors, and I feel lucky to have good neighbors.

I live in a small town in South Carolina. It is a quiet place. This town is known for growing peaches. It has a lot of farmland. Many houses are on the land. They are usually two stories high. Some have metal roofs to keep cool in summer. Others have gray shingles on the roof.

The town has a few stores. There is a stop light in the middle of the town. This is where the stores are. You can find food at three places: a Chinese restaurant, a Mexican restaurant, or a burger place. There used to be a pizza place, but it closed.

There is a small pharmacy where you can buy some things. They are famous for selling Cherry Coke. There is one grocery store, IGA. People often buy only a few things there. Many go to a bigger store in another town called Walmart to buy more.

The most popular store is Dollar General. It sells many everyday things. Many people go there. There is a furniture store with a pet groomer next to it. The store has been there for a long time. They will even move your new furniture for you.

A doctor and a vet are in the next part of town. They help the people of Johnston. We have an elementary school in our town. Students go to middle and high school in the next town.

There is no park in our town, but they are building one. It will be a small park. We do not have a movie theater, bowling alley, or other things to do. But it is a nice town. You might pass by it without noticing it.

I first heard about my city on a podcast. It was about people who had disappeared. I was surprised. The cost of apartments here is very high. More than $1,000 per month. I had never heard this story before. Neither had my friends. Life is hard. Many of my friends cry at night. We have learned to be careful with money. We like cheap things. We like the smell of old toys and old clothes. When you grow up, you don't smell as much. Some people smoke. Some people are used to living like this. But the old market is always there. The smell of old magazines is strong. It gets into furniture and stays even after you clean it.

There are three second-hand stores near my home. If you start at the far end, you can visit two charity stores, a library, a rare book store, and a curiosity shop. The city is busy. Cars and people fill the streets. But the stores are quiet. It is a good place to spend an afternoon. The city is growing. Many people come here. It reminds me of New York. Everyone is busy with their own things. No one asks too many questions. You can be alone and people will leave you alone. It is not like the South. In the South, people care a lot about each other. Here, people respect your privacy. You can be alone as long as you want and the city will be quiet.

I like my neighborhood. There is music coming from next door and people singing upstairs. It is a lively place to be. We live together in our building, but we are like friends. We help each other when we need it. We celebrate birthdays and help at funerals. I am lucky to live here. My neighbors are kind to me. We help each other. I clean up after myself and they do the same. We take care of each other's mail. It is nice to see them. I think they like me too.

I live in a big, modern building. But my neighbors make me feel at home.

My home is in a typical neighborhood. Many houses are the same. They are well-maintained. A group called the homeowner's association helps keep them this way. The front yards are similar. There is grass, small stones, and short driveways. Some houses have two cars in the garage. The streets are in good condition. They are paved and have no holes. Most houses are one story, but some are two stories. We do not use a regular mailbox. Instead, we have a big group of mailboxes at the end of the street. Everyone needs a key to get their mail. We also have big boxes for packages. The HOA likes things to be the same.

My house is on the edge of a city. It is a mix of rural and city. We have a lot of space. There are community pools and walking trails. We can walk our dogs or go for a walk by ourselves. It is a safe area. Many people take care of each other. Some people are retired, but there are also young and middle-aged people.

The city is big, but it feels small. We have many things we need. We have a large store with many shops. It takes about 15 minutes to drive to any important place. Then we have many stores to choose from. We have expensive grocery stores and cheap stores with few items. My neighborhood is safe and well-maintained. We have nice things like pools and walking trails. We can drive to any store we want.

I live in a small town. It is near a big city. The city is to the west. My house is on the east side. This side of town is not very rich. Many houses are rented to or owned by people who do not have a lot of money. But it is not a bad place. My neighbors are friendly. When I walk outside, they say hello. Crime rates are a little higher than in other parts of town. There have been some bad crimes in the past ten years. Someone was shot near my home recently. A man was killed by a gun near a bar. Luckily, we have not had any big problems. Sometimes, we forget to bring something inside and it disappears from our porch. Many people in my town have a problem with opioids. This is a sickness that can be fatal. There are many places to help people with this sickness. There are rehab centers and training for families and friends of people with this sickness.

My son goes to a good school. The school is for young children. The teachers and staff are very good. My son has a special need, but he has not been bullied. He loves his school. The parents at the school are very involved. They plan many activities to help the school and the families. The school gives food to all students. No child goes hungry. The school is fair to all students, no matter how much money their families have. The city is making some parts of the town better. They are fixing roads and parks. But the east side, where I live, does not look as good as the other parts. This is a problem for my neighbors and me. We like living here. People are friendly, the school is great, and there are stores to buy what we need. Our home is not very valuable, but it is okay. We have lived here for 16 years. We do not want to move.

My neighborhood is full of culture. It is on a hill. Many old buildings are there. I live in a 7-story apartment building. It is across from a old theater. A block away is a fun bar. People go there on warm summer nights. There is often a long line to get in. A few blocks away is a big park. The park is for the city. It is surrounded by hard concrete with big stairs. In cold winter months, homeless people put up their tents in a line on the sidewalk. They keep their tents close together. This keeps them warm. They are near a place where they can take showers and use the bathroom. What I like about my neighborhood is the people. Hilltop used to be a very bad place. There was a lot of gang violence. The people did not forget. They tell stories about it. The people work hard to keep the neighborhood clean. They care about their city and their block. Some people say you should not walk around the Hill at night. I think this is not very nice. I think it is because of old ideas about people. I am a little bit dark. I think the people on the Hill see me as one of them. They are kind to me. They have helped me many times. I feel happy when I walk on the streets at night. I meet nice people. They help me when I need it. I feel safe in my neighborhood. I feel alive.

I live in a small town in Michigan. It is in the country. Our town is near lakes. We have Lake Michigan and Lake Charlevoix close by. These lakes are very pretty. People can go swimming in them.

We do not have big cities with many stores. If we need something, we must drive to get it. Our town is very quiet. People are friendly. They know their neighbors.

I like my neighborhood. Houses are not very tall. They are old and some are new. Some homes have basements. Many homes have yards with big trees and flowers. People have pets, like dogs. Some people have gardens in their yards.

In the summer, children play outside. They ride bicycles and play on trampolines. Adults walk their dogs and ride bicycles too. People wave to each other as they pass by.

The streets are clean. People take care of their lawns. The grass is green and short. People keep their bushes and flowers trimmed.

Our town is a safe place to live. People feel happy and peaceful here. We have a police station and a health department nearby. We also have a place to recycle and a park. Our town has baseball and softball fields. We can hear the announcers calling the games. We can also hear airplanes flying by.

I like our town. We can walk to get ice cream and to the park. My children can ride their bicycles to the park. It is a great place to live.
